1.body: Rivet's goal is to be a very powerful programming language and at the same time easy to use, with a syntax that is the result of mixing Go + Zig + C#, and by other languages such as Python, Lua, TypeScript, D, etc. Rivet uses the C programming language as its main backend. Before continuing, I assume you know how to use a console, otherwise you can read this tutorial: The Linux command line for beginners .

3.body: The compiler requires Python 3. The Rivet compiler currently generates C code, so a C compiler, which supports C11, is required to generate executables. Over time the compiler will add support for generating binaries directly without the need for a C compiler. The compiler has been tested on linux . Just execute python3 rivetc some_file.ri. You can see all available compiler options by using the -h/--help flag. python3 rivetc -h
3.title: Dependencies

4.body:
Let's start with the typical Hello World!: We create a file called hello_world.ri with the following content: import std/console; func main() { console.writeln("Hello World!");
} Then we compile that file: $ python3 rivetc hello_world.ri We'll get an executable called hello_world as output, so we run it: $ ./hello_world We should see this output: Hello World! Excellent! You have compiled your first program in Rivet!
